Job Summary:
The National Security Policy Directorate at Public Safety Canada is looking for talented and highly motivated people to join our workforce as junior policy analysts. Successful candidates would support and take leadership roles in vital areas of national security, such as:
a) Info-sharing - making sure that relevant national security information is properly shared among jurisdictions and national security agencies in order to better protect Canadians;
b) Transparency - finding innovative ways to make the national security community more transparent with Canadians, with the goal of promoting trust and accountability;
c) Bias Sensitivity, Diversity and Identity - leading ground-breaking policy work to mainstream diversity considerations in all national security activities;
d) National Security Review - coordinating with the national security review bodies such as the National Security and Intelligence Committee of Parliamentarians (NSICOP) and the National Security and e) e) Intelligence Review Agency (NSIRA);
f) Passenger Protect Program developing and implementing innovative policies and programs to keep travelers safe while working with civil society to ensure the protection of civil rights;
g) Counter-terrorism policy and counter-proliferation policy assuring that the Canadian government is coordinated, and has effective tools at their disposal to mitigate the threats posed by terrorist organizations, violent extremists or proliferation threats;  or,
h) Research Security focusing on policy tools and programs that ultimately assure the protection of Canada's cutting edge research.

Job Responsibilities:
Work description and tasks: Successful candidates will learn about the Government of Canada's security and intelligence community from a practical perspective, including the activities of key partners, how they interact with one another, and current national security policy priorities. Responsibilities could include:
a) Research and analysis;
b) Assistance in developing national security policy;
c) Development of briefing and communication products;
d) Fostering and maintaining relationships with other national security organizations;
e) Support in events and training logistics; and,
f) Coordination of, and participation in, interdepartmental intergovernmental, or public meetings.

Required Skills:
Skills and Aptitudes Essential Criteria
a) Ability to work in a dynamic and fast-paced environment;
b) Work collaboratively and demonstrate strong interpersonal skills;
c) Ability to work independently and be self-motivated;
d) Strong problem solving, organization and time-management skills
e) Creativity, innovation and initiative;
f) Ability to provide high quality research and analysis; and,
g) Strong oral and written communications skills (bilingualism is an asset)

